4. C: Yes, fine!\
5. H: Let\'92s go then, right now. You have enough time to go, right?\
6. C: We'll go! Say, on the road you\'92re taking are there many Northern Thai [2] villages?\
7. H: There are lots of them. As for Northern Thai, there\'92s no shortage [3] of them! There are one or two villages.\
8. And a road for motor-cars reaches almost up to our fields over there.\
9. Yeah, this village right here [4] is Northern Thai.\
10. All of these many trees by the roadside here belong to the \'93Big Boss\'94 [5].\
11. And there ahead of us there\'92s another Northern Thai village.\
12. All these tea orchards are also Northern Thai.\
13. Not Central Thai folks.\
14. Yeah, and we have to draw water [6]. From right here. To drink in the fields.\
15. C: Isn\'92t there any water to drink up there?\
16. H: No, there isn\'92t. We scoop up all the water here that we use everyplace in the fields\'85\
17. Hey, how about rolling ourselves a cigar, OK? One for each of us.\
18. C: Yeah, that\'92d be great.\
19. H: Oh, when you make a cigar to smoke in a banana leaf it\'92s very harsh.\
20. Here, take it, when we make them in corn-husks, they smell great.\
21. Here, you smoke one too!\
22. Just grab those matches over there!\
23. This cigar is hard to light [7]! It\'92s a little too wet.\
24. C: Whose tobacco is it?\
25. H: It\'92s the Kachin\'92s [8] tobacco! Yep, it must not have been well dried, this tobacco. You can\'92t light it.\
26. Hey, these plantations here are where we Lahu pick tea to earn money. [9]\
27. What\'92s hanging high up on that tree over there is a honeycomb.\
28. Have you ever tasted the juice [10]?\
29. C: We have tasted the bee-juice before.\
30. H: Did it taste very good?\
31. C: Delicious!\
32. H: There are twelve nests hanging there. Now, this year there aren\'92t that many of them hanging.\
33. The path to where we draw water to drink is up a very steep slope.\
34.When we carry the water we must go along bending our heads [forward to keep our balance].\
35. This road here is the one that we usually walk on.\
36. So it\'92s not far now until we get to the fields.\
37. When we reach that saddleback [11] up there in the mountains, we\'92ll be able to see over to where the fields are.\
38. Look over there! Those people tilling the fields, they\'92re our Lahu folks [12].\
39. <shouting to the workers> Till the fields well, till \'91em well now!\
40. We\'92ll take a picture of your backs!\
41. Field-worker: What are you looking for?\
42. We\'92re just visiting. Well, you\'92re tilling the field. Don\'92t exert yourselves so much!\
43. If you don\'92t have anything to eat and drink you\'92ll have no strength.\
44. Really tasty food\'97pork, chicken [13].\
45. Prepare the food properly and 
\i then
\i0  work.\
46. Then you\'92ll have the strength.\
47. If you don\'92t have food [14] to eat you\'92ll have no strength when you\'92re working in the fields.\
48. If you should hook [your tool] onto a tree stump you could topple over backwards!\
49. So cook delicious curries to eat [before working]. [15]\
50. There\'92s an awful lot of hard work to do around here.\
51. If you guys drop dead, [your hard work] can\'92t follow you [to the grave]. So take it easy!\
